76561198277440387,Recommended,253250,30943609,Posted: 4 April,all,an idiot with a sword,"Stonehearth is a game about building a small town, with the help of a group of 'hearthlings' who build, mine, farm and craft their way to victory (sometimes) over ever-stronger groups of enemies. You have an amazing amount of control over the appearance of your town, and you can custom build every house, road and wall. There are a variety of decorations and tools to place around your village, and there are two main storylines to follow (if you aren't playing on peaceful) - fighting the enemies, and becoming a township. You also get to pick one of two types of hearthling: The Ascendancy, who live in the forest, or Rayya's Children, who live in the desert. They have slightly different skill trees, so the gameplay is a little different.The hearthlings in the game have basic personalities, and the newest update (Alpha 21) brings likes and dislikes. They have attributes too, which make them more or less suited to certain jobs. It's easy to pick up which attributes make a good soldier, for example, but some of the other classes are more complicated. This makes for an immersive town, where new arrivals' talents can mean the difference between life and death for your people.Crafting in the game is simple, and you have the (amazing!) ability to easily queue multiple items, and even request that you always have four beds in storage, for example, so you don't have to intimately micromanage every item crafted. Items placed in houses you design will also automatically queue to be produced by your crafters and placed, which enables the game to run smoothly. Even if you don't have the ingredients to make the chair you want, if you place one when you design a house it will be built and placed as soon as the ingredients are ready. There are a variety of crafters, from the carpenter to the herbalist, and every town will require a different approach (as each map and every hearthling is random). You can farm a variety of foods, including animals, and mine the hills around your town for ore. Traders will visit, and you can sell them products or buy goods.The only downside I can think of to this game is that it is not complete yet. However, I've loved watching it develop over the last 565 hours that I have played, and I can't wait to see the finished game in the future. I am excited for the new types of hearthlings planned for the future, in particular. (And if anyone on the development team ever sees this: I'd love to have some of those pet fighting wolves for my hearthlings, please!) I really feel like the development team listen to their audience, and I have been very impressed with the quantity and quality of the work they are putting into this game.I would recommend this game to anyone who enjoys minecraft, terraria, the sims, simcity, cities skylines, stardew valley or animal crossing. It has beautiful scenery, and great animations. You do not need a powerful setup: the game runs smoothly on my ACER Aspire F 15, which does have a dedicated graphics card (NVIDIA GeForce) but which is not a gaming laptop. I have minor lag when my town reaches 25+ hearthlings, as the candles flickering at night make my computer slower. I find that toggling the walls down on my buildings at night solves this entirely, and it's really not an issue."
76561198107099871,Not Recommended,253250,25732996,"Posted: 27 September, 2016",all,Airman First Class Dumpkins,"The one thing I must stress for those of you who are interested in this game is this: it is for all intents and purposes in early access. I know many of you have played early access games, and some of which were fully fleshed out games with minor bug fixes needed. THIS IS NOT ONE OF THOSE GAMES. As well as the numerous ui, ai and graphical errors there seems to be about 10 hours of expansive entertaining gameplay, after which you are left with a feeling of ""what else can I really do"". Now thats not to say that the devs have abandoned this game, in fact the situation is quite the opposite; there exists online a roadmap layed out of all the updates and new features they wish to add on. However as it currently stands I cannot recommend this game AS A STANDALONE TITLE. It doesn't have enough content to merit the $25 price tag, that doesn't mean you shouldn't purchase it: it means you shouldn't purchase it for what it currently is. If you buy this game it will be a game you have to revist it again and again in hopes that the devs actually deliver. So for right now I say wait, follow this title, add it to your wishlist etc. but don't purchase it yet."
