,Recommended,253250,23939580,"Posted: 29 June, 2016",all,inspiringdeeply,"I'm writing my review pretty early despite not having much play time so far.I bought this game during the Seam Summer sale at 20% off after having put it on my wishlist a while back.So far, the game is definitely worth the buy- and has shown itself already to be highly replayable even at its current state. I'm writing my review with the understanding that there will be a few bugs, some improvement suggestions, and in mind that more content will be released. Honestly, with where it's at now, I would love for a Workshop to be added for the community. Alas, it's still in alpha...Graphics: 9/10 being pixel themed. Very cute chibi like, so it appealed to me immediately. They glitch out sometimes for me, but I don't find it too annoying to not play.Gameplay Mechanics: 6/10 (this is definitely subject to change) With the fact that as others have stated there is much need for improvement for AI to properly work. I wish that the tasks they did were in order of your selection on what to build- meaning if you choose to build a cottage and you're currently building one- they will flock to the cottage you just qued instead of continuing to build the current one first.A way better tutorial on how to use the game mechanics at this point is highly needed. I had to google with no help to find out how to place a objects, such as my crafting bench, and had to press ""P"" to finally be able to go to a screen to place objects. After pressing P, I have not needed to do so, and placing objects started working for me. I would have also liked to understand how to use certain classes like the trapper early on.For the first part of your gameplay, you'll probably find yourself very slowly starting to understand how the game works because there is a lack of even a brief tutorial. The only tutorial you get is understanding how the camera options work, which if you play games regularly especially of this type, is pretty self explanotory before you even open the game.Content: 6.5/10* (subject to change) so far there are two playable races and two types of biomes to play in. The races pretty much work best only in their biomes- so if you're wanting to switch it up game play will definitely be harder. Not a bad thing, but I hope to see more races and biomes added for sure in the future which they've shown to be highly likely in the start screen.You are also able to select to be in Sandbox mode, normal, and hard, of course.I hope to definitely see a wider selection of crafting, building types, tasks, enemies, classes, etc. in the future. Once again, it's still in early acess- but even with its options now it's not bad.One complaint I have is that at the beginning of the game, you choose a selection of the map- make sure that the box you pick is not cut off in anyway because that section of the map is the only available area for you to build your village in at least in what I've seen so far. I hope that they change it to where that's just the area of the map that you choose to reside, and still can explore out further. Otherwise, it cuts a huge chunk of game time to me. You can't explore much out of your settlement, and it makes resources limited.Replay Value: 9/10 With the options so far that are available, you still have different scenarios and ways that you can play out in your game. And it's pretty addicting...Reccommend: 10/10 Would reccommend anyone this game at its current state even in early access.Stonehearth has already shown itself to have an extremely promising future. Hope to play with this game as it grows and expands itself. Hope to see DLC and a workshop in the future. :)"
,Recommended,253250,33730784,Posted: 22 July,all,Wanderhoof,"ALPHA REVIEW IN PROGRESSThis simplest way I can describe Stonehearth is that it is a sandboxy, fantasy-medieval themed, town/city-builder and villager sim.  If I had to make comparisons to other games... oh, geez, it has dashes of Minecraft, Warcraft (the old RTS), Harvest Moon, Sims, and maybe a few others.  But, it isn't exactly like any of those, and I am not sure the comparisons due it full justice.The art style for the world is cheerful and cartoonish, being somehwat block styles a la Minecraft, but with more detail.  I would say that it would be nice if the in-game character graphics were more like they are in the splash screens - a chibi-manga style with soft, rounded lines and a warm, distinctive appeal.  This is sort of my one major disappointment.  The splash screens have characters that seem... well... full of character.  Distinctive, interesting, unique, and full of personality.  In game, they are reduced to a blocky archetypes that visually aren't too striking.  That said, praise should be given to the detail, such as is available, given in customization, with hair, facial hair, skin tone, gender, and name all being customizable, while various traits and skills can be endlessly re-rolled for random personalities, abilities, strengths, and weaknesses.While there are, depending upon game mode chosen, very likely optimal paths of building, defense (for the regular and hard modes),villager promotions and job assignments, resource gathering, and so on, Stonehearth seems perfectly happy to let you muddle about in whatever fashion you choose.  While some may find a lack of specific development direction dictated to them by the game (via quests or a campaign, as examples) to be a turn-off, I quite enjoy just being able to approach things at my own pace and with my own ideas.Quests do periodically pop up, but they aren't terribly critical in how you pursue them or even if you pursue them.  They seem more like a bit of variety tossed in should you want to participate in them or progress your village in a certain direction or attain specific achievements and rewards.There is a lot of customization you can do with how you build and decorate structures.  But, you can also choose from a variety of pre-designed structures for easier village building.  Placement is easy enough, and there are suitable features for facing, editing, and placing your buildings so that you can get the village layout you desire.Even though various things - job promotion, assigned activies, and crafting for villagers are spread across a handful of menus, navigation of these menus and villager management is fairly intuitive.  One downside, however, is that when building new structures villagers seem completely oblvious to existing items store in stockpile and instead of using those will craft entirely new items to decorate said structures.  This is not a terribly big issue, as any surplus items can easily be sold to merchants.Given this game is still in alpha (though, amazingly functional none-the-less), I don't have any glaring issues or complaints thus far.  However, it would be nice to see at some point the tutorials fleshed out a lot more.  As it is, figuring out custom buildings and also how various buildings, resources, villager jobs, and so on interact with one another is one part reading every item, job, and resource info pop-up, and one part trial-and-error.  I'm not even sure this is really a bad thing, per se, but it does take some time to becaome proficient and informed on what does what and how.All in all, I love what has been done so far, and I am hopeful and excited about what comes next for Stonehearth.  Just as it is, I feel like paying for this early access alpha was money well spent."
