,Recommended,253250,23454140,"Posted: 8 June, 2016",all,BJSwensen,"One of the greatest Alphas I've ever seen. Period.Want to hear the details? Well, my fellow offspring of Rayya, sit tight for my story will be a long one.It's hard to begin describing what's so good about the game.Is it replayability?Great community? (and believe me, I don't treat these words lightly)Catchy art style?Responsive and responsible team?Warm and fuzzy atmosphere of cuteness?Before Alpha 16 Stonehearth, while interesting, was a barebone system. Now it's a game, and with the new hard mode it's challenging exactly how you want it to be. With multiple military classes and new difficult enemies able to break through your doors you get yourself dragged into the turmoil of battles trying to keep your little sandbox settlement safe.What games does Stonehearth resemble? Suddenly, Dungeon Keeper. There is no dungeon, yes. But the same ""indirect control"" and ""build your town"" principle is still here, and voxel retro graphics gives you the right nostalgic vibe.Thanks to Stonehearth I have discovered Discourse - a free and open-source web 2.0 engine SH forums are built upon.Thanks to Stonehearth I got myself deeply interested in voxel graphics. And finally installed Blender.This game is built with love. But more than that, it is built with extreme mod-friendliness in mind, that, I won't fear to say, I've never seen before. Information is in an easy readable format. For every task, there is a free software available. If there is a downside, it's that skilled programmers are yet to turn their attention to the game.For those who like looking at a pros/cons list (I'm one of those types), here's one.+ Already playable and very enjoyable+ Watch and influence development through Discourse forums, Twitch streams and Trello feature lists (with voting for feature priority)+ Easily moddable (including translations, many are already available - check the forums)+ Quite playable without any mods (unlike that dragon-slaying bestseller RPG)+ Nice, if somewhat simple, 16-bit stylized voxel graphics+ Create building templates, then share them (or not)+ Nice music+ Active development (unlike some other titles, Stonehearth is an example of an Early Accessdone right)+ Rabbits- BugsBe ready for them. This is, after all, an alpha. While there is backward save compatibility now, I recommend starting a new game with every new major Alpha release. Some bugs have workarounds. Sift the forums. Stick to stable builds if you don't want to risk and make in-depth testing. Report bugs to the forums.- Lacking pathing and priorityThe cause of unfinished buildings in 80% cases is that hearthlings can't get to the next queued block with current scaffolding. Try building more ladders manually. It gets better with every major alpha, but still has issues.- The price is arguably a bit too highI'd like to mention separately some things that are planned, butnot there yet:- No water physics- No weather effects/seasons- Some classes are missing (namely Magmasmith and Geomancer - yes, you will be able not only do digging, but raise mountains as well). As of Alpha 17, Engineer is in development.- No multiplayer (it's late in the dev queue). I'm amazed how playable the game iswith no multiplayer yet.- Diversity of items is comparatively poor. Will be fixed, but the eyes of the devs' right now remain on gameplay (which is, in my opinion, totally justified). So no Cthulhu... yet. Can be somewhat fixed with mods (but still no Cthulhu).- Building mode is still limited and lacking (gets better with every major Alpha though)- The number of biomes is currently limited to 2 (will be more). You can try fan-made ones.- The number of playable races is currently limited to 2 (will be 3 or so)You may think the review is full of flattery. Your right. Make your research, see for yourself. All and all, with no revolutionary things in the box, Stonehearth can still be your heartwarming casual pleasure. The source of modding frenzy. Or both.The choice is yours."
