,Not Recommended,253250,30318308,Posted: 4 March,all,BatsInTheCave,"When I first saw the trailer for Stonehearth, I was immediately attracted to its style, town management and building mechanics. It reminded me of Banished, a game that I also enjoyed, so I decided to buy it. After the dozen or so hours I put into it, I was found quickly bored and frustrated because of three mainly reasons:1. Population GrowthThe rate at which I was gaining citizens was painfully slow, as in the game, you to have a certain amount of wealth to attract the next villager into your town. This is what I also find annoying about having to start new saves as it was a set back to my previously impressive kingdom that I grinded in another save file.2. A.I. PathfindingI cannot count the amount of times I would have my villagers refuse to build ladders for a newly dug mine. This might seem obscure to a person who has never played this game, but when three of your citizens in your already small town (because of poor population growth) are stuck doing nothing in a mine, the town's productivity is gone and the game grinds to a halt, and it's frustrating! I then have to try and speculate to why they were not building the ladder that would get them out of the mine, so I reloading the save, deleted the ladder's blueprints and then adding them again and it starts to make me feel like a moron who thinks turning their computer on and off will remove a virus!3. Creating buildingsAnother aspect that I thought would be fun was the building mechanics of the game. I was quickly shown otherwise as I was swiftly discouraged from using their complex and bizarre building system. Its hard to describe, but think of trying to build a house in the Sims, but with no clear formatting of what should go where and having to place every single block at a time. Maybe I such at building, I don't know /:However, for the time I did play, it was fun. I enjoyed the art style of the cuboid people, living in a cubic world and eating cubic food. I also found great pleasure when mining. Finding that first gold ore was overwhelmingly satisfying.I do believe that these problems that I have issues with will be fixed in patches that will better polish the game's flaws. But so far, the biggest problem that stands is that THERE'S NOTHING TO DO! You can grow your town, but for what purpose. The newly joined villagers will be turned merely into food workers and with nothing the military can fight or do, besides monsters that almost three shot your workers, there's no overarching goal like finding new and interesting technologies/problem solving situation or anything of that matter. If you are not a scrub at the game like I am, comment on what you can do in game please.I truly hope I haven't offended any veteran of the game, but I'm just hoping to inform problems that a newbie like ""I"" have faced."
