76561198121400420,Recommended,253250,32501085,Posted: 17 June,all,MikeRobe,"Tentative recommendation. If you're willing to overlook the exceedingly long dev time, Stonehearth is a decent builder game with some light action.You start off with very little as either a desert-peoples or a feudal-peoples,and can pick a location to match. I've always liked city builder games and Stonehearth really scratches that complete control over the process. Well, sorta. You draw up blueprints that you can make from templates or design completely yourself (my favourite part) and then give your workers orders to build them. The AI is a lot better than it was, and now will only never finish a building 1/15th of the time.Occasionally you'll be distracted by goblins and kobold attacks, which you'll fight with an archer, footman and cleric and go back to building. The content noticeably peters out as you play and you're left with very little to do apart from expand and beautify your city. That said, watching things get built is like a drug, it's very easy to just watch and watch and watch. I do like this game, I really do - there's just not enough content for a 4yr old game with a sizeable dev team.If you like building games and your favourite part of Emperor: Rise of the Middle Kingdom was building wonders, you should get this game. If you're looking for Dwarf Fortress, probably not for you."
