,Recommended,253250,24966732,"Posted: 16 August, 2016",all,Leapordnight,"I wholeheartedly reccomend this game. It's in Alpha right now, and it's fantastic. If it continues like this, the finished product will be a gem among god-like resource management games.Pros:1. Citizens (Hearthlings) that actually ""think"" for themselves. Feed themselves, clothe themselves, the whole shebang. Just assign them to a job and watch them go. They even run away from monsters, which I really appreciate. Unless you manage to strand them on top of a mountain, they're going to be fine.2. A really nice crafting system. Easy to manage, as precise as you want it to be. Personally, I like to set things up so my cook always has food on the table, but I let my blacksmith run wild between mining trips. Again, the Hearthlings do everything on their own.3. Building Construction. What I really like about this is the scaffolding the hearthlings construct around the building, consuming wood but giving it back after the building is complete. It's a really nice touch, in my opinion. The buildings are easy to design and look great when they're done. I would like a little tweak to one thing, but I'll talk about that later.4. Challenging Enemies. Basically, if you get into some deep trouble, all of your hearthlings are dead. I sacrificed one of my first footmen to a Varanus (the smaller variety) and it proceded to slaughter the reast of the town. The things that attack you in this game are genuinely terrifying, unless you watch seeing tiny litle people who depend on you for survival die.5. Actually a sort of story line. I won't go into too much detail, but there is some interesting stuff going on in the world around you. Goblin Warlords, Ogres, Necromancers, and something called Squirrel People? (They probably won't appreciate me eating their brethren) There's a prophecy and everything. I, for one, am fascinated.Cons/suggestions:1. Performance issues and low framerates. This is probably just my computer. It's pretty out of date. Beware people like me: this game does not run at even 30 FPS on older machines. Probably an issue that will be lessened as developement continues.2. Minor glitches regarding construction/buildings. The hearthlings will occasionally stop building things that are only half complete. As far as I can tell, this is an issue that occurs when loading a saved game. It doesn't happen very often now that Alpha 18 is in place. Also, game devs, I would like a tool to move up and down the floors of buildings while constructing them. So that if I have two floors, I can make the 2nd one invisible and just look at the first. It would make placeing things on the walls a whole lot easier. Please and thank you.This game is totally worth your money.(Oh, and whatever you do, don't place that decorative scout gong too soon. Trust me)"
,Recommended,253250,25042933,"Posted: 20 August, 2016",all,Sora,"To put simply this game is Age of Empires meets Minecraft.It is still in Alpha, so obviously there are still bugs, however the game is completely playable right now. The only issue that interfers gameplay wise as far as I can tell is building, if you design complex and large structures sometimes your hearthlings (citizens/people) will have trouble completeing it and handling objects. Keeping this in mind you can simply use the command console to instant build the building or just build it in easier to manage chunks, and if there is scaffolding or ladders left up just use the destroy command in the command console to remove them. Furthermore, if you see that your hearthlings have yet to place an item there is a good chance you simply put it ontop of a block above the path they can take, in this case just build a ladder and take it down after the item is placed. I know you may be thinking, I shouldn't have to do this extra junk to play the game, but again it's in alpha still and the ""extra work"" is like an extra click.All-and-all this is a very fun game that gets even funner as they add new stuff and c'mon if an Alpha version is already fun and awesome then the completed will be even better."
,Not Recommended,253250,23522244,"Posted: 12 June, 2016",all,Kosher Potato,"This can be a good game.This probably will be a good game.But not yet - it's extremely far from being completed and I'd strongly discourage anyone from paying $29 for it in its current state.Edit 11/5/2016: Definitely seeing some improvement in the game, would like to reiterate both parts of my review - still not worth it, but definitely on the right trackEdit 9/17/2017: Coming along, but still very slowly. I like the direction this game is headed but it's so very far from complete.Major improvements since my last edit:* Game engine is much more polished, bugs and crashes are very rare.* Villager AI much better, they don't get stuck mid-construction anymore.Still missing:* Crafting system is uninspiring. I expect better from a game that revolves around crafting and building.* Game is still missing a sense of direction, there aren't enough clear goals to build towards* UI is very clunky and takes too long between transitions.Still a thumbs down from me - will try again in 6 months"
76561198292930117,Recommended,253250,23150309,"Posted: 22 May, 2016",all,Yangkoete,"A couple notes on playing the game;Have at least 1-2 Farmers. Once you make one of them a cook, they help harvest, but you still need them to plow the fields.Workers are VERY much so necessary. Although the carpenter, potter, mason and other occupations do help build/haul, you're going to want to keep the people with low-ranks down on the worker size (1, 1 and 2 for the body/mind/spirit; Keep them a worker)Fighters and such need to be the most populace unit category (Archers, Knights and Footmen); At least have one of each with an herbalist. (For the three, high Body and Mind. Mostly so they don't run like cowards)Herbalist and Cleric; Have one of each. One heals while the villagers sleep/get into beds, one heals just by walking around/in combat. (High spirit for these guys is necessary)All ""Worker-class"" occupations need mind and spirit. All three are much so needed for the farmers than anything.ALWAYS. ALWAYS remember there's a pause button that lets you keep playing. Helps you plan things.Town watch; Love it, use it, learn it, remember to turn it off after everyone is done fighting.Always go after goblin camps/""stray monsters"" after the next invasion summon (Ents/Golems/Etc), that way your villagers aren't defenseless."
