,Not Recommended,253250,22109525,"Posted: 28 March, 2016",all,[ZSU] Strongbow,"I've been looking at this game for a while now, something told me to stay away from it, but I gave in and grabbed it on a city builder binge. I'm sad that I did.I like the defence/survival element of Stonehearth, where camps of enemies will spawn around the map and periodically attack your settlement, you can either attack them early and risk your guards, or just wait out the attacks for the XP. There are also loot boxes and such around the map to be discovered, usually guarded by some mini-boss creatures. That part they did right, it's fun.For a game that's been in development for such a long time, I really wonder why there are so many bugs. I understand it's a early access game, but that's not really an excuse for the really terrible building mechanics. It's a city-builder game, if i was developing a city builder, the first thing i'd get sorted would be the building mechanics, at the moment they're extremely frustrating and unintuitive. You have no ability to change things once you've placed them, so if you want to extend your wall out by 2 squares, you need to undo everything you've done to get back there. This is really frustrating when building and planning complex structures.I'd like to see defensive walls (properly) added, or at least the ability to create stand-alone walls outside of the custom structure editor, for a simple project like a perimeter wall the player shouldn't be forced to stuff around too much. I noticed also that it's very clumbsy at sticking to things. i tried to incorporate a pre-existing structure in my town into the wall, instead the custom structure editor decided that the sections of wall touching that building now belonged to it, and not my wall, so the only way to get rid of those walls was to destroy that building. Annoying to say the least.Along with numerous bugs that caused my workers to get stuck on window ledges, placing objects is a real pain. I've been forced to build a cobblestone fence piece-by-piece because if i try to place more than one at a time, the workers freak out and wont complete the task.At this point I can't reccommend the game, I feel like I was ripped off, to be honest."
,Not Recommended,253250,31597708,Posted: 6 May,all,CossonWool,"TL;DR: It's nice that the devs haven't abbandon this game, but for 25 USD it's not good enough for the current price, preformance or content.The game is essentially the same as a year (or two+, memory fades) ago, here's what I think is new.Enemies have been added, the stall has been added, mood is new, maybe? there was somthing similar before with food so it's hard to say, new combat classes have been added, seeds being traded so you can get exotic plants is new; no advantage in gameplay though, some factions quests and prefabs... can't recall any new other features.What I'm getting at that all that's significantly changed is combat, it's a city builder type game so the actual content updates seem very lacking.Enemies are now annoying to fight; before you'd simply look at hearthlings stats and equipment and think ""should be able to tank alright"". There's no new way to guage encounter sucess however the hearthlings take five times longer to finish similar fights, because of kiting, which can be seen as good for strategy, however now it's simply annoying for time.There's still no way to build grass coloured tiles although ground does reappear when you remove flooring, it's impossible to cover up pre-existing holes and holes that are made while excavating. Landscaping's impossible.There's still a limit to the amount of harthlings that can work on diging at a time making efficiency through population only possible if you devide easy large tasks into, slightly less easy to manage, small tasks.Things I was expecting when I revisited this game.Bosses, or any boss. Chuthelua was teased in pre-alpha and as far as I'm aware, there's no way to get it to appear in game.More environmental features; like biomes or setpieces. there have been no new features since I stopped playing.The dessert was added as a seperate world generation option which while I found strange, I could understand this was probably entirely due to the Rayya's children. Looking back on it, it would have been much nicer to see these two features simply added to one game world; a dessert biome mixed with forest, with you being able to start with both ascendincies (idk spelling) and rayya's children, then the plants in each biome could be attained to get seeds for foreign crops rather than the current ""trader appears"" kind of event currently being used.The lack of setpieces is disappointing, the stone rabbit heads where added so why can't there be more? Rather than trading with magical traders that neatly drop all the loot by the flag, have a trader outpost setpiece. Quarry setpeice, Goblin setpeice, Wolf mountian/caves, oasises surrounded in grass, trees and food, a boss setpeice. Given that rabbit heads have already been added and the goblin event spawns a goblin camp, I don't see why unique and interesting setpeices aren't already in the game.It's nice that the devs haven't abbandon this game, but for 25 USD it's not good enough for the current price, preformance or content.If devs see this, give the hearthlings a ladder animation, it should be basic considering how many idle and movement gestures you gave them already."
