76561198048550478,Recommended,253250,23660998,"Posted: 19 June, 2016",all,bsworks,"This game has a lot of good things going for it, and I think it'll get better.  The villagers and enemies are stylized in cute manner, and the little plot dialog that exists carries the cute theme as well - but that doesn't stop some battles between the two from being deadly serious.  Combat is simple once you figure out how to develop your battle team to survive with the difficulty curve (two tanking armored characters, backed by archers, with a cleric thrown in will get you by the majority of the battles).  I can easily see more event battles being added as this game progresses but it would be nice if enemy bases  spawned more often around the map - perhaps sending their own raiding parties.However, the real bread and butter of this game is customizing your village exactly the way you want it.  This is the most complex part of game play and it takes a while to get the hang of.  Editing a blueprint is tricky and time consuming at first but I highly recommend saving one to greatly reduce time later.  If your Hearthlings stall during mid-construction, check your available recources needed, then try manually placing ladders in case they cannot reach the upper construction areas.  (I highly recommend a building blueprint that has doors and window frames, but no other furnishings or decorations which can be added later.)What's really needed here is more terrain options like adding soil blocks for leveling surfaces and undo'ing building mistakes.  Far too often I found myself relying on back-up saves because nudging a building over 1 or 2 blocks or fixing an errant click while digging is not very forgiving at this point.This game is good so far, and it's going to get better.  Highly recommended."
