,Not Recommended,253250,31986203,Posted: 26 May,all,bunihunny,"Bought this game a while back, thinking the concept was interesting and I liked the more close-up style of management as compared to other similar games. I can't remember exactly how my first few play-throughs went, but they were bad enough I deleted the game for a long time without reinstalling it until very recently this last week. I played the game slightly obsessively for the first few hours, working to maintain my colony and not be overtaken by the Golbins trying to kill us all. However I quickly encounter many problems that just annoy me to the point I don't want to play anymore...My first two setups things were going fine, until one big raid of Goblins came and killed everyone. I watched helplessly as all my villagers slowly died and then restarted. Same thing happens again, even though I had tried to focus more on the military aspect of the game. However, with a meager 20 max villagers my military was really lacking.I decide to quit the game and come back to it with a stronger military force later the next day. It goes well, I pass the raid and huzzah! There's pretty much nothing interesting after that, other than my game freezing constantly,  my villagers getting confused and breaking, or an engine error popping up and forcing me to restart the game. I tried both the unstable latest patch and the offically release stable patches. Both failed me...and also after enabling the unstable patch just to see if there were any updates at all, which really there aren't  (then disabling after it crashed even faster than before) all my custom buildings broke and if I tried to place them the game crashed once again. Had to delete them all and start over. Fun stuff!Pretty much the game is exactly the same as when I bought it, and it's just as unplayable and annoying as before. Pawns will stop building things mid-build, people will starve in holes instead of building a ladder to get out, and the village numbers are so meager you'll never really have fun with masses of items or pawns. Also, there's a 3000 item limit on the game, this includes buildings and inventory. You will quickly fill your inventory and quit the game like I did on my third play-through. I regret thinking it might get better and not getting a refund...UPDATED 9/28/17 - Decided to give the game another try...figured with all the updates there might be something interesting. I also increased the item/person cap to 50 hearthlings, wanted to see how many my computer could handle since this is such a hungry game. I finally got through the entire ""Quest for Township"" and managed to build a decent town, and for a while I was thinking ""Wow, I might really need to change my review to a positive one.""But! And it's a big one...there's literally nothing after you construct the (3) gongs other than getting your♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ed repeatedly. I survived through all the trials, with a population of 27 hearthlings. 15 of them were dedicated to round-the-clock security, because after you defeat the Tribe Masters that come to challenge you (or whatever they are called) the♥♥♥♥♥rape just DOES NOT STOP. I was clicking R *RUN TO SAFETY* every 5 seconds. Seriously. It got to the point that my hearthlings couldn't even farm...plants were dying in the fields because I had to call them to safety points so often. Things on the map could no longer be gathered or created because if my hearthlings went two feet from the troop of guards, BAM, here come the goblins + kobolds + ogres to ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥up. Also couldn't change their job or turn off the ""job"" cue to just make them haul, because then...BAM! Goblins come. So there was loot just littered around the map that was essentially untouchable for my hearthlings. When the guards cue for job was paused...they don't defend. Everyone dies, nothing gets hauled. Yay! Multiple invader groups would often show up at once as well, with mutliple Ogres in each troop along with archers and clerics and some swordsmen. Because of these large scale invades happening all at once I ran into another massive problem...Broken doors. Ogres can smash through them, and that's about all they do. I had one structure in particular...just finished, four doors. Almost instantly, three Ogres show up to smash all four doors (instead of fighting the troop that is right next to them. Makes sense, right?) This doesn't seem like a huge problem...until you realize they don't get replaced. Ever. Never ever. Not unless you remove the whole building. This is such a huge flaw for me, that lead to me entirely abandoning the town...I cannot deal with a thousand doors around the colony with tiny little hearts next to them - or worse, entire buildings with shadow blueprints for doors that will never be replaced...On top of this, I was being invaded so often (I timed it, about every minute n 25 seconds) that I had no hope of completely removing and rebuilding the structures without everyone dying in the process. It was  a nightmare late-game to say the least.The 20 hearthling slow-down is still very much so a thing. Unless you have some series power and ram, don't expect to get over 20 hearthlings. I have 16gb ram with an I7 6700K 4.00GHZ processor, and the game ate it up and spit it out like it was a joke once I hit my 27 hearthling mark (but it was already well slowing by the 20th hearthling). I also noticed the prereqs for getting more hearthlings becomes obscene in the way of foods. I can handle accumlating large wealth, that's easy and it makes sense. But large masses of foods makes less sense to me...yea I should have enough to feed all of them but, why do I need 2500 stacks of foods along with 13,000 wealth for a single new colonist? Seems a little...impossible when half your food goes bad in the pile before your three cooks can even touch it because you're being invaded again (and the cycle continues...).I would say I enjoy the building aspect of the game, which is the main reason I would tell anyone to try it out at all. It's very rewarding to see some of the structures come to life and to really get a feel for how you want your town laid out. However, this is also flawed in that you can't delete walls after they are placed (sometimes.) I don't understand why it happens, but during building planning the walls won't undo or erase...just super frustrating when you are halfway through a building and you misplace a wall.Overall, I would say the game in it's current start is a solid...5/10? Worth buying/playing but only if you REALLY like building things with super limited items and being able to see how happy/sad your colonists are.(Honestly, I would just go with Rimworld. It's not 3D, no, but it's so much more playable at the moment.)"
