,Recommended,253250,30973804,Posted: 5 April,all,Mystery,"Built a city only to be destroyed by a Goblin raiding party, So ♥♥♥♥ing♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥11/10"
,Recommended,253250,30972275,Posted: 5 April,all,Hypocritical_Oath,"It's a 3d dwarf fortress-lite game. There's not much more to say about it. It's quite fun, the technology tree is pretty interesting, and the economy, while static, adds another neat mechanic to the game. This is definitely what's good about this game. These are the best parts.However, it's not wholely good. There are problems with it. The building template system is obtuse and workers will get confused and be unable to complete buildings quite often if not given very, very generous space. The way that special potions work, and how the Herablist works are both hard to understand, and not taught to you whatsoever.Workers also have a hivemind kind of thing, they'll all clump onto a single task instead of spreading themselves amoungst it, I understand that this may be to lessen computing power needed, but it also has some less desireable effect. For example, farmers will harvest one field at a time, which can cause you to lose crops or just simple be stuck harvesting carrots forever if you have enough of them planted. Same thing happens with mining, hauling, etc. This doesn't happen with crafters, as they'll split they're work in a more intelligent way, but you're still constrained by the queueing system.As far as enemies go, there is a point around day 20 where you get hit with a large wave of enemies, if you're not prepared then it is game over. That's not so great, but honestly it's a neat way to game over people that are trying to be as peaceful as possible, and who ignore their military.There are also serious performance issues. Every villager seems to have their own mindset and their own tasklist and their own traits, etc, etc. They perform relatively independently, outside of gathering/hauling jobs, like I noted above. This brings about performance problems though, as they probably are not wholely optimized quite yet, as this game is still in alpha, and your CPU will get a thrashing.Something in the game is also stored poorly, or at least that's my best guess. The game uses mountains of RAM after you've been playing for a few hours, like crash your computer amounts of RAM. Restarting it helps this, but it builds back up to insane RAM usage after another hour or so. It seems the further I go into the game, the faster the RAM builds up. I doubt that it's a memory leak, and I'm convinced that it's because of how the game stores it's voxels or how it stores the player-made buildings. This is a serious problem, and I doubt it'll be fixed anytime soon, as it's been around for months now.However once the game is feature complete, I'm sure the devs will devote tons of time to optimization, as they should.So, to sum up this rambling, if you like indie and alpha games, and you like Dwarf Fortress, and don't mind tehcnical problems, then this is a definite buy.If you can't stand that stuff, want a professionaly complete game, or just don't like dealing with technical issues, then it's probalby wise to take a pass on this game, but you really should check in on this game again when it's finally released, or at least in beta."
