,Recommended,253250,34051818,Posted: 5 August,all,Solariser,"Don't expect this game to be released, because at this rate it never will. It feels like one guy is working on this game and working to get it out of early access all by himself. We know he won't do it, he knows he won't do it, but he does it anyway.Despite that though, it's a good game, it's not worth the full price but if you can grab it on sale it's definitely worth it. You are able to build any structure you want and the hearthlings will work out how to use it and pathfind as intended. There are occasionally a few bugs with custom made structures and it can be a little fiddly as it's not always clear what the problem is, but it works fine for the most part.The map never feels too small, and whether you want to live outside or hermit inside a mountain you are able to. The difficulty stops and peaks when you get to about 14 hearthlings, so don't expect too much in the way of that. There is also little reason to actually leave your village and explore the camps that spawn, but they add some life into the game so why not have them?I also do want to mention their support is amazing. If you have a bug or issue and you post it on the forums with evidence as to how it happened, even better if you have steps to reproduce it, you'll get responses to the problem within a few days where they'll actually test it themselves and give feedback.There is quite a lot of content in the game to mess around with, and it will take a good amount of time to experience it all so it's definitely worth a shot - just don't expect it to be done anytime soon."
,Recommended,253250,34043783,Posted: 5 August,all,Scruzzer,"I was looking for a 3D Rimworld, and this comes pretty close. I feel more of an emotional attachment to dwellers in Rimworld, but this does a nice job. I've been having a great time with it so far. It's a solid colony manager/builder focused on directing individual dwellers to do jobs and advance the colony.The potential for creativity is great here, but one big drawback here is the building UI. As long as this thing has been in development, the UI should be greatly simplified and responsive. If you like precision and detail in your buildings, you can do it, but they DON'T make it easy. Walls are unneccesarily built with columns on the end which greatly complicate what should be a very, very simple task. You know how easy it is to build in the Sims? Well, the developers of Stonehearth don't. The custom UI layout makes me think they've seen the Sims, but the execution of the UI makes me think they never actually played it. Something as simple as deleting a wall doesn't even exist in Stonehearth as far as I can tell.This is sad because I just end up going with the pre-desgined buildings to save me the headache of struggling, so the colony isn't 100% built by me.Mining can also get frustrating as the AI has the ability to trap itself from time to time. Make friends with ladders and learn how to cancel a mining zone in order to save you some frustration.Despite the building woes, it's still a fun game that I would recommend to fans of the building/creating/managing genre."
